I could go off in any direction about the ramifications of this, whether it be politics or pop culture, but I feel like it's harder to connect with others because we really lack a unified mainstream these days. 

And I say that as someone that's always been into "obscure" stuff.

And this creates divides (both harmless and harmful) where someone thinks that they're "tuned in to what's going on" and get frustrated when someone else has no idea what the hell they're going on about.

With the UNGODLY amount of options available you have no choice but to pick and choose what you're going to spend your limited time on, and that's probably not going to be the same thing a lot of folks around you pick and choose

The interesting thing about living in a post-internet world is the "mainstream" no longer exists. 

There was a time when everyone watched the same tv shows, went to the same movies, and got their information from a limited number of sources.

That's all gone now.

THE MATRIX RESURRECTIONS

Loved it.

The few criticisms I saw of it don't make a lick of sense. Did we see the same movie?

The meta-narrative at the beginning is a great commentary and totally works in context as well. Not an easy feat.
(forgive me for hijaking your tweet but) the universe keeps screaming at me to get Project: Akimoto up and running, don't it? https://t.co/a0nkPdfQLn
They definitely left the door open for more with that ending, though. And after a quick stretch it's on to the main event: The Matrix Resurrections.

The final fight being in the pouring rain narratively because Agent Smith is an overdramatic bitch amused me. But it's indicative of my larger problem with the sequels.

Pt 1 had something to say and had amazing visuals. Pt 2 and 3 seem to be more about the visuals than story.

The introduction of the short haired fighter annoyed me just because I knew she was dead the second she showed up on screen.

The kid having a big damn hero moment feels so odd when you have to know his story by watching The Animatrix.
The opening scene better establishing the existence of "rogue programs" in the Matrix (The Machine City?) sets up a lot that isn't touched on too much, and I'm hoping Part 4 deals with it.

Matrix Revolutions thoughts!

Definitely better than Reloaded, as there are like...stakes involved, instead of the pursuit of a macguffin at the behest of a plot device.
Time for dinner and then The Matrix Revolutions, which I have never seen before.

And one last bit of criticism that I wonder will be addressed in part 4
Everyone in Zion is hot. Outside of the Chancelor no one's got a drop of fat on them. And it could be argued that living conditions in Zion means everyone is ripped but nah that's bullshit some folks get fat.

But really, everything from the Oracle's return on out is way too long and drawn out, and is really just everyone hunting down the macguffin that is the Keymaker because the Oracle told them to. It serves the narrative, but I found myself getting bored. The fights were too long.

There are some interesting bits in the script that just make narrative sense: Neo being treated like Jesus in Zion, but not everyone believing Morpheus, and the telegraph of the "twist" at the end with the Oracle and the Keymaker talking about fulfilling their purpose.

The Matrix Reloaded thoughts!

I totally see why I walked out of this 18 years ago with no desire to see part 3. But as an adult I don't have as many problems with it.

Still got problems, though.
And yeah, rewatching this with the knowledge that it's an allegory for trans experience. The whole Agent Smith "deadnaming" Neo thing rings especially loud.

Co-opters of a certain metaphor miss the point so god damn hard. Morphues even has a line describing what these folks are actually about: "so inured, so hopelessly dependent on the system, that they will fight to protect it."
